actor.name: Amazon
actor.description:
Amazon strives to be Earth's most customer-centric company where people can find and discover virtually anything they want to buy online. By giving customers more of what they want - low prices, vast selection, and convenience - Amazon continues to grow and evolve as a world-class e-commerce platform.

Founded by Jeff Bezos, the Amazon.com website started in 1995 as a place to buy books because of the unique customer experience the Web could offer book lovers. Bezos believed that only the Internet could offer customers the convenience of browsing a selection of millions of book titles in a single sitting. During the first 30 days of business, Amazon fulfilled orders for customers in 50 states and 45 countries - all shipped from his Seattle-area garage.

Amazon's evolution from Web site to e-commerce partner to development platform is driven by the spirit of innovation that is part of the company's DNA. The world's brightest technology minds come to Amazon.com to research and develop technology that improves the lives of shoppers and sellers around the world.

actor.name: Amazon
actor.description:
Amazon strives to be Earth's most customer-centric company where people can find and discover virtually anything they want to buy online. By giving customers more of what they want - low prices, vast selection, and convenience - Amazon continues to grow and evolve as a world-class e-commerce platform.

Founded by Jeff Bezos, the Amazon.com website started in 1995 as a place to buy books because of the unique customer experience the Web could offer book lovers. Bezos believed that only the Internet could offer customers the convenience of browsing a selection of millions of book titles in a single sitting. During the first 30 days of business, Amazon fulfilled orders for customers in 50 states and 45 countries - all shipped from his Seattle-area garage.

Amazon's evolution from Web site to e-commerce partner to development platform is driven by the spirit of innovation that is part of the company's DNA. The world's brightest technology minds come to Amazon.com to research and develop technology that improves the lives of shoppers and sellers around the world.

This isn't religious freedom, it's keeping women in their place.  Think about that next time you go into one of their stores. They don't value and respect you, they want to control you.
In my life I have found most these people hiding behind their religion to be the biggest frauds
I am a Christian and I have a huge issue with Hobby Lobby cherry picking the issues they claim bother them so much.

Hobby Lobby just used their imaginary friend as an excuse to get out of paying for health care is all this is about. There is no deeper meaning, there is just a frugal company weaseling it's way out of taking care of it's employees regardless of beliefs. Just one more example of an imaginary friend being used to try to get someones way and one more example of how religion should be nowhere near politics.
Yep they buy from a country that forces abortions; they invest in companies that make birth control (non abortive) that they wish to deny to their workers; I'd call that hypocrisy.  Yep.
It is hypocrisy, and should be called out. Would Jesus do what Hobby Lobby is doing?

A. Take a look at the items in your own houses and think about where you purchased them. Most household items/toys are made in China, Taiwan or Indonesia. 
B. HL pays their full time employees 14.50 per hour and their part time workers 9.50. That's considerably higher than other retailers.
C. 401k investments are determined by the 401k manager not by the owners. Employees Choose which funds they want to participate in, not the owners.
D. HL is more than willing to provide 16 contraceptives out of the 20 approved by the FDA for the HHA. 16 contraceptives people! If you can't find something that works or unwilling to use one of those 16, you have a bigger issue to deal with. Take responsibility for your behavior. Better yet, make your partner take some responsibility too. 
E. Birth control pills cost about $8-10 per month. You spend way more money on your Starbucks or Dunkin's each week, which probably aren't as important. The "morning after pill" costs $30 a pop. Do the math. And if you have to have to get script for this or buy it a head of time, that means you intend on having unprotected sex. Seriously? Why would anyone do that with so many risks out there.
If you don't think your company has any business deciding what medicines you take then you shouldn't demand that they pay for it. Keep both government and business out of your bedroom by taking care of this yourself.
F. Maybe, just maybe, men should start being held responsible for this issue. Isn't it about time?
As a Christian of deep faith it makes my blood boil when I see the hypocrisy of companies like Hobby Lobby and that of other so called people of faith.
It's just time to stop buying their stuff and shopping there.  Stop supporting hypocrisy.

For the record and for the sake of sciencie: ocp are not abortives neither avoid implantation as it is wrongly assumed by the people having an religious argument . However they do treat diseases such as polycistic ovarian syndrome and endometriosis which are debilitating for any patient . As any other medication it has to be monitored for side effects . The terrible issue here is the precedent that has been set up   for public liberties and rights by the Supreme Court ruling yesterday . Any employer can use the religious argument to save money for themselves and avoid covering these medications in their  health insurance  . Very wrong as the decision did not use medical evidence .
And yet they WILL cover vasectomies and viagra....hmmmmm, something of a double standard, isn't it?

it is ok to order cheap crap, which I will say i also use to buy, from China where abortion is legal to get rid of a fetus if it is a girl and start over hoping for a boy. They need to follow their Christian values in all things they do and believe, not just what is convenient.

Their religious principles go out the door when they place orders to china for their cheap junk made by slave labor and by women forced to have one child! Where are your principles when you place your order on Wall Street for abortion pill stock!  You don't get to pick And choose when your are going to be a Christian.
John Huffman. I am Jewish and I do not force my employees to eat kosher nor do I restrict what medicines they take even if they're made from pork. I do not bring my religion into my workplace.

Well, Christianity and hypocrisy go together well.  This company gets most of its products from a country with one of the highest abortion rates in the world.  And they also invest in companies that manufacture the very birth control methods they weaseled out of covering.
The ruling made Corporations over People stronger !
these 5-4 decisions are based on political affiliation and conservative agenda=not  morality or points of law and or justice=sickening
Wasn't it only 4 medications that they refused to cover, while covering 16 other kinds of contraceptives?
Prime example of a  "pseudo-christian" attitude. The Greens are total hypocrites, their true God is the almighty dollar.  :/

As a Christian I refuse to shop at a store that refuses healthcare to women. What a step back in women's rights.  Healthcare decisions should be made with a healthcare professional not your employer(old white men)!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!

text.text: Rarely drop the F-bomb, but this warrants one. Stay tuned for a blog piece on this later today, posted on That Blog Is So Takei.
So corporations are people, fetuses are people, but women are just receptacles and incubators.  Thanks for clearing that up, Supreme Court.  We appreciate your regard.

Wait until a Muslim owner of a "closely held corporation" seeks to deny all Haram medications and treatments to his employees, and see how fast the "religious rights" crowd runs away from this decision.....

And it's a crafts store that buys a lot of its merchandise from China, which has, shall we say, enforced somewhat liberal abortion policies. Hobby Lobby's owners seem to have rather malleable, profit-based beliefs.

I've said this elsewhere, but my feeling is that if an employer is going to provide prescription coverage as part of its health plan, then it has no right to dictate what prescriptions it will cover. It should be all or nothing, period.

from Justice Ruth Ginsberg "Would the exemption…extend to employers with religiously grounded objections to blood transfusions (Jehovah's Witnesses); antidepressants (Scientologists); medications derived from pigs, including anesthesia, intravenous fluids, and pills coated with gelatin (certain Muslims, Jews, and Hindus); and vaccinations[?]…Not much help there for the lower courts bound by today's decision."
Does this mean that atheist shop owners can refuse to hire Christians?

They have a job, what's stopping these people from purchasing their own birth control?  Or purchase a different insurance?  Or have it covered by their partner's insurance?  Before we committed to the vasectomy WE paid for, we paid for our birth control.  If I remember correctly, just a couple years ago this was considered a wonderful compassionate family conscious company with insurance for part timers, fair pay, and Sundays off.

It's not about birth control!!! Stop allowing yourselvesnto be distracted by the real issue here. This is a corporation who's personhood is MORE important than the personhood of an individual.  Namely, a woman. That means that WOMEN AREN'T PEOPLE according to this ruling. Religious freedom ends when it gets in my face. Any person has the right to believe and practice how he or she sees fit. That person does NOT have the right to impose his or her own religious beliefs on me, end of story. Except now SCOTUS says yes they do because Hobby Lobby and ANY other corporation who decides to folllw suit has more right to being a person than a woman. I guarantee if this was a man's issue, this argument wouldn't even exist.
An illustrated guide to american personhood.
I don't understand how a corporation can make life choices and decisions for their employees. I am a man and being a man I have absolutely no say what any woman of any age does with their bodies!
they are against it for their religious freedom but I am pretty sure most of their crap is made in China where they abort more children then we give birth to in a year.
And, it's a store that will never see another penny from my purse! (Or any money for that matter!)

So does that mean that since I object to eating meat for 'religious reasons', I don't have to provide a lunch hour for my workers out of fear they might eat a ham sandwich, or does it mean I still have to provide them a lunch hour, but can restrict what food items they can consume during it?  If they eat a ham sandwich, I am technically paying for it, since the money they used to purchase the meat came from their paychecks, which I provide, so shouldn't I have the right to decide what food items are available for them to purchase?

Does anyone read?!?!?! They cover birth control!! Just not plan b, I agree with the ruling your boss should not have to pay for your oops! Read you dumbasses don't take everything you see on FB for the gospel

That's what I keep wondering. The court decisions keep referring to a religion, and I keep wondering "When did Hobby Lobby become a religion? I could have sworn it was a store!" And for the record... I'm a Christian.

Even you are falling for this?  The ruling was NOT about religion being forced upon people, it was government mandate being forced on people.  So many people are just wrong about this ruling it's exasperating.

I was completely shocked by their decision - it's like they have no clue what the ramifications of this precedent are going to be while the rest of us can clearly see this will only be the beginning of limiting our benefits and discriminating against anyone they basically want to based on religious beliefs...isn't that religious persecution?
Hey guys, here's an idea, get a national health service like we have in Britain. Every man and women has access to contraception whenever they want it for free!
If you want to know what this ruling really means, don't believe anything from ideological sources from either side. There is a lot of misinformation out there to suit the various agendas.
This just opens the door for companies to refuse to provide coverage for any treatment they don't "believe" in.

If people don't like a company's health plan, they can find employment elsewhere. That's the way it always has been. Only Obamacare has forced socialized medicine on the US and removed free market decisions. In no way has the access to birth control been hampered. The decision (only possible because Obamacare is mandating that a private business owner pay for their employees pregnancy prevention decisions) simply states that the government can't force a business owner to PAY for the birth control. When did an employees DESIRE to have someone else pay for their contraception trump a private citizens right to support their own religion?
So if we should no longer pay for things our religions disagree with, do people against wars get a tax break?
People saying that they still cover 16-20 forms of birth control, it's not about what they offer. It's about the reason for which they don't offer all of them.
Shall we continue to pretend this was ever about religious freedom?

actor.name: The Richard Dawkins Foundation for Reason and Science (Official)
actor.displayName: The Richard Dawkins Foundation for Reason and Science (Official)

text.text:
Sloppy studies and poorly ran tests do not constitute good science. As such, any "evidence" produced from these agenda-based mockeries should be rejected as bunkum. 

Read more here: http://ow.ly/yCY3G

This is true, just demanding evidence for a claim is not enough.  It has to be GOOD, high-quality evidence, because crappy evidence can be (and often has been) used to "prove" nearly any claim from flying saucers, to the existence of god or bigfoot, to autism being caused by vaccines, to the conspiracy theory of your choice.

It's a post-hoc explanation:  Do it first, find answers later.
Usually a bad method of science, since you already have the conclusion in mind.
"Poorly run." Seriously, grammatical errors like this undermine credibility.
So why do you promote Anthropogenic Global Warming alarmism? I have never seen one of the articles critical of that stream of pseudo science on this page. Does that not suit your political agenda???
Murray are you posting on the wrong article?
This man is a snake oil salesman
Science does Not have all the answers ( yet) so we can not reject something just because we can't explain it scientifically.
Some say that God healed them of all their ills not based on any scientific study or evidence, that's even more disturbing!
Please fix that gaping grammatical error. It should read: "poorly RUN tests" not "poorly ran". Ugh.

The reason why I admire Richard Dawkins is because he claims that any  kind of research without proper evidence has to be discarded, irrespective of its stream in "actual" science or any other stream. That is the key part, imo. :D

Can we stop with the grammatical error comments now? 15 comments in and 3 people have pointed it out. We get it. Seriously, you don't have to say anymore on the subject. Feel free to keep pretending like you've never made a grammatical error and didn't immediately fix it.

(Edit: I fixed my own error before 3 more people pointed it out too.)

If you reject it for reasons of experimental design or data integrity, and it is of concern to you...it is your responsibility to fix the flaws and do the experiment properly.  Otherwise...just live and let live, yo!

Murray, the evidence behind Climate change is tremendous, it's supported by 97% of published papers by climate scientists, and, among the skeptics of climate change who actually are climate scientists and not TV weathermen, not a single one of them denies that the Greenhouse effect (increases in Carbon and other greenhouse gases cause retention of heat in the atmosphere) is a very real phenomenon.  On top of that, are you familiar with Richard Dawkins?  He is not known for being a left-wing liberal.  
Why on Earth would you post a completely irrelevant polemical statement of science denialism, accusing someone of political views they don't have, on a Facebook page that you're supposedly a fan of, when the actual topic of the post is one you presumably agree on?

I will admit I go to acupuncture. I do not believe in any of the pseudo-science, or spiritual aspect at all. I figure one of two things is most likely happening. I'm either reacting to the simple feeling of the needle hitting the nerves. Or it's a placebo effect. Either way, it's doing something for me. It did nothing for my wife. But if it's a placebo, I'll still take it. Because I need relief, in my case for what were daily headaches. It my do nothing for you. And it may all be in my head. But as long as I'm ok with that, I think others should be ok with me doing it.

Katayoun Irani - we should not go around accepting claims without valid evidence to support them. The fact that science hasn't explained some stuff is only a reason to wait till it has, it's not a reason to accept any old garbage in the meantime.
Rick, if you want endorphins, you may as well eat a spicy pepper.
This is why no one believes Dawkins is behind this site. "Poorly-run" would be correct, and consistent with the rest of the post.
No, "poorly-run" would be wrong. Don't need a hyphen with an adverb.

A very interesting article indeed. And James Roberts - (one 'like' of your comment above is mine; I fully support it) - permit me one comment on the grammatical error : 

>>>John Christopher Santry "Poorly run." Seriously, grammatical errors like this undermine credibility.<<< 

- John C.S., and your seven 'likes' - sometimes a "grammatical error" is simply a typographical error, and no way affects the credibility of the information being offered, nor of its author or poster. Given the earned, high credibility of the RDFRS, I suggest that is the case here: a simple (unimportant) typo. Jumping so fast and only to that as a comment deemed relative or important suggests a loud cry of "Wolf" unnecessarily.
Its function is as a compound adjective and the point is to be consistent. The subject-verb agreement is also questionable, tests are not always 'run'. 'Conducted' might be better.

text.text: Get employers out of healthcare. That's the root of this problem. Ready access to routine and necessary medical resources should never be dependent on income or employment status. This is the underlying evil we must end.
Don't be surprised when the American Taliban decrees women should not be allowed to work - period. I support a boycott of Hobby Lobby.

Exactly, as a Catholic Myself this is dangerous dangerous territory, what about Jehovah witnesses? they don't believe in blood transfusions, or if a child is born out of wedlock, would  they have right to deny that child health insurance because it goes against their religion? this has nothing to do with religious believes and everything to do with the war on women and take away their power and their ability to chose.
Hobby lobby, you pissed off most of the shoppers that you have....can you say bankrupt?
Ginsburg made good points about some religious groups being against almost any medicine. Should those groups be discriminated against? Religion and government need to be separate!

Religion/Beliefs shouldn't trump civil rights. This is extremely dangerous. Allowing a company the use of  religious objection opens up a huge can of worms. Hobby Lobby doesn't seem to be offended when they are making money from immoral investments and selling goods from China. Good thing it's against my religion to shop there. LOL

So what the SCOTUS is saying is that I can have a deeply felt belief (even one that is scientifically incorrect), claim that it is part of my religion (even though it is never mentioned in any of the religious texts) and use that as a basis of discrimination against one segment of society.

What those dogmatic relics sitting on our country's highest court just did is endorse a religion for the entire country. 
What is not being discussed enough about this ruling is the agregious ridiculous attempt by five male justices, in order to justify their ruling, have denied OTHER RELIGIOUS BELIEFS the opportunity to use this exemption despite how deeply held their religious beliefs are!
These justices went against previous cases when state supreme courts voted against discrimination based on religion, for example,  Bessinger v. Deloach who claimed his religion mandated segregation and Equal Employment Opportunity Commission v. Freemont Christian School who claimed religious freedom in order to pay women less and deny married women health care because the school claimed their Christian faith states men are head of households and women belong at home. 
The oligarchs at the Supreme Court are literally selling our democracy to the highest bidder. In this case it's looking like a theocracy for the United States.
By the way, the Greens used their hobby lobbying to enact a bible class in an Oklahoma public school, Mustang High School. Does this school also offer a Quran studies class? Of course not, in fact they explicitly said it only applied to Christianity. 
Who doesn't see the perversion of religious liberty to practice your religion now being used as a means to indoctrinate and force religion into our supposed capitalist secular society.

Exactly. Ruth gets it. You don't even HAVE to go a step further to violate the establishment clause. The continued language of "sincerely held religious belief" implies some measure of that is sincere or insincere, religious or nonreligious.
That is all irrelevant.

Employers buy an insurance plan. Whether the employee and his/her doctor use that plan to cover blood transfusions (a no-no under some deeply held religious beliefs) or birth control pills is NONE of the employer's business. Your employer is "paying" for your birth control only in the same sense they are "paying" for it by giving you salary that you'll end up using to pay for it.
I don't see how this can pass. What about those employers who have sincerely held non-religious beliefs. Why is the religious person getting special treatment?

Ìt seems very few of my American friends realize the oddity of having basic health plans care managed by employers. All other Western countries have basic health care plans which are essentially independent of employers although many have "complementary plans" provided by employers (often sector wide complementary systems). What is incredible to foreign eyes is the enormous power given to employers merely by attaching health coverage to employment. This is akin to an old practice: bondage. What it says to any employee is this: if you loose your job, you not only loose a pay check but your family loose health coverage. To anyone with the slightest health problem in his family, this is an odious blackmail, pure and simple.
You have to hand it to SCOTUS. This is a brilliant way to please both the anti-worker Libertarians and the anti-woman Theocrats. And it's all cemented together with delicious, creamy corporatism!
'Merica! Home of the religious nuts and land of the corrupt.
Can my anti religious views allow me to require that the religious be on anti psychotic meds?
I suspect their sincere religious belief is against any sort of minimum wage. Sooner or later they will bring that up.

So sad to see that the AHA is actually staunchly religious. You have replaced traditional religion with the religion of statism... Respect everyone's beliefs.. You are free to consume whatever you wish, you are not entitled to force others to pay for it.
It is against my deeply held religious belief to spend money at a store that discriminates against women.
Can a Muslim-owned company require its female employees to wear burqas? Or are deeply held religious beliefs only protected for Christians?
War and killing violates my ethical standards. Shouldn't I be exempt from that portion of taxation?
Its amazing to watch this nation being pulled under by the religious right. This is very scary stuff!

What I wish to emphasize is the tact that religion is the last frontier of social behavior that is no longer ordered from above, but mostly by unenlightened individuals, who, in this country, very often have not even studied theology but have simply read the Bible or other sacred scriptures. They raise themselves very often with the aid of a coterie or gang of similar minded individuals who are simply interested in perpetuating their own attitudes toward their religion. 

A true faith in God, in any divinity, while still wishing to proselytize, must at least be enlightened enough to maintain some objectivity in order to insure that the individual being proselytized is fully aware of what he or she is doing. 

What I perceive is that too many of our so-called preachers simply lack the respect for the individual mind and spirit as too many of these preachers are simply intent, by hook or by crook, on enslaving individuals to believe what they believe and never really let the individual reach that conversion on their own, out of their own conviction and their own inspiration and real interested willingness to believe in the God or divinity that is being - quite often marketed with all the marketing techniques of any earthly product... see, for example, how quickly such religions have created their own dating services... just to better enslave individuals who would not have even thought of that faith otherwise. 

I find it extremely sad that religion in this country and in so many other parts of the world continues to be an excuse to enslave people instead of honestly and sincerely trying to enlighten them without coercion and/or abuse of powers.  

Evangelicals in this country have become the RELIGIOUS RIGHT that has sold out to republicans and to the NRA and the KKK and other such organizations that feign to promote freedoms but are actually dishing out slavery and dependency under new forms of total dependency and inability to think correctly and in tune with the true spirit within us. 

God, I am convinced, whether he is the god of Christians or Jews, or Islam or Buddha... or what have you... is not interested in enslaving individuals to do what earthy busy bodies demand... but what the spirit orders them to do and I do not perceive such a spirit moving among us as a people... I see only earthly organizations and institutionalized religions that have become much too secular and too corrupt to have earned the right to enslave people the way the religious right is enslaving people today in this free land of ours where total separation of church and state was arrived at precisely to prevent such abuses from taking place. 

I say this with all due respect for all my friends who call themselves believers and men and women of faith. I ask only that they examine their own souls and stop paying homage to institutions that are - I am absolutely certain - not the work of any god, but the work of organizations out to manipulate people for political and social motives that are not a part of religion or faith but simply a method to market certain political objectives of the right. 

That is why they use all means and all sorts of money simply to manipulate humanity into a form of slavery that is alien to any free thinking individual.
I think that it shouldnt be my employers duty whatsoever to be required to pay my health insurance.

This is all such a joke. Hobby Lobby's insurance plan has NEVER paid for the morning after pill, nor IUD devices. They still pay for other forms of contraception. This entire case is about the Government sticking it's nose where it doesn't belong.

actor.description:
Through innovative, reliable products and services; talented people; a responsible approach to business and global citizenship; and collaboration with our partners and customers, Samsung is taking the world in imaginative new directions.

● Samsung's Leadership, "A World-Class Company"

From our beginnings as a small trading company, Samsung has evolved to a world-class corporation with businesses that span advance technology, semiconductors, skyscraper and plant construction, petrochemical, fashion, medicine, finance, hotels and more. Our discoveries, inventions and breakthrough products have allowed us to be a leader in these fields, constantly pushing the industries forward.

● Samsung in Our Life, "Bettering Everyday Experiences"

From our innovations in consumer electronics to our developments in biopharmaceuticals, Samsung shares impactful experiences each day with people around the globe. Through our devotion to create superior products and services across all areas of our business, we strive to enhance the lives of people everywhere and bring positive change to the world around us.

● Samsung Creates Possibilities, "A Corporation of Discovery"

Our purpose is simple: It’s giving you the freedom to take journeys; to discover new experiences; to take charge of your world. It’s the power to connect who you are today with who you want to be tomorrow. In a changing world, we’re changing faster. We are relentless in our pursuit of discovery and innovation, creating technologies and providing services that empower.

● Samsung's Contributions, "Committed to Social Responsibility"

We measure our success not only in our business achievements, but also by how well we serve our community, protect our planet‘s resources, and make a difference in people's lives. We embrace our responsibility to contribute as a good citizen, taking action around the world to foster a better society, protect and improve the environment, and strengthen our communities.

text.text:
Our Pathway to Exploration Should Start with the Asteroid Redirect Mission

More here: http://bit.ly/1sSDtpV

Despite its rejection by the NRC Committee, we argue that the Asteroid Redirect Mission (ARM) is an affordable and logical first step in a sequence towards a sustainable human space exploration program. ARM is not only consistent with the NRC Committee’s own principles, but is also the only near-term initiative that can shape their recommendations into such a program. ARM would launch U.S. explorers into deep space beyond the Moon, and fits logically into an exploration program aimed at Mars.

A few connected thoughts:  I agree that the asteroid redirect mission ultimately gets us some out of LEO experience, maybe some confidence.  The last time we sent humans into a high orbit to repair Hubble, we had to have a rescue vehicle waiting on the pad.  How can we think about going to Mars if we can't even refuel the James Web scope in its planned Lagrange orbit? We will never be a space faring civilization until we quit the hand wringing and learn to take risks.  Get on with it,but let's have some small victories along the way.  This is a journey, not a destination.

Just spread a rumor that there is oil in space. We'll spare no expense invading it and won't even bat an eye at the financial cost or potential disasters which come from it. Hell, we won't even notice when we don't get any oil out of the deal.
Might said mission also teach us a little about redirecting asteroids away from Earth?

Well put, Mr. Henderson.  We've become too risk averse.  Space is an inherently dangerous place and our means of accessing space carries no small risk.  Missions will fail and people will die as humanity spreads beyond its home world; that is a reality we must be prepared to accept.  No one stopped to count the bones of those who died in previous waves of exploration and we must not pause to do so or we will never go anywhere.
Keep calm. Congress will come unglued, and start throwing money at manned space exploration, the moment the Chinese get a taikonaut any higher than LEO.

As someone who's interested in researching asteroids to learn about the primordial solar system, this mission excites me.  It doesn't have the glam of the Apollo landings or a crewed Mars mission, but it will greatly advance our understanding of planetary science.
We should send humans to Mars now. It's time already!

Forget deep space missions, deep space or even near space mining (on the moon and NEO's) could make the concept of material wealth more or less obsolete, there is so much up there we could rapidly expand human civilization for tens of thousands of years without worry.
Some bastard will turn this into a doomsday weapon someday. I can see the 22nd or late 21st century nightmare... A doomsday cult redirects an asteroid into a collision course with Earth.

content.queryString:
Our Pathway to Exploration Should Start with the Asteroid Redirect Mission

More here: http://bit.ly/1sSDtpV

Despite its rejection by the NRC Committee, we argue that the Asteroid Redirect Mission (ARM) is an affordable and logical first step in a sequence towards a sustainable human space exploration program. ARM is not only consistent with the NRC Committee’s own principles, but is also the only near-term initiative that can shape their recommendations into such a program. ARM would launch U.S. explorers into deep space beyond the Moon, and fits logically into an exploration program aimed at Mars.

text.text:
This week on #SetiTalks: 'The Gemini Planet Imager: Initial Performance and Data Analysis' with James Graham on Tuesday,  7/1/14 at 12:00pm PDT.

The Gemini Planet Imager (GPI) is a dedicated facility for directly imaging and spectroscopically characterizing extrasolar planets. It combines a very high-order adaptive optics system, a diffraction-suppressing coronagraph, and an integral field spectrograph with low spectral resolution but high spatial resolution. 

Join us to learn fascinating details of GPI observations of Beta Pictoris, which clearly detect the planet, Beta Pictoris b, in a single 60-second exposure with minimal post-processing. Full details here: http://buff.ly/1nVrboB

text.text:
Astronomers may be closer to proving gravitational waves with precise measurements of rapidly rotating neutron star.

When Albert Einstein proposed the existence of gravitational waves as part of his theory of relativity, he set in train a pursuit for knowledge that continues nearly a century later. But although the weight of evidence continues to build, undisputed confirmation of their existence still eludes scientists. Researchers have now provided another piece of the puzzle with their precise measurements of a rapidly rotating neutron star: one of the smallest, densest stars in the universe. Eric David, the author of U.S. Air Force's $7.5 million Study On Teleportation (2004) considered several possible forms of teleportation, including what he called  p-Teleportation or Psychic Teleportation (the idea of people vanishing from one place and mysteriously reappearing in another) which could be closely related to e-Teleportation or Exotic Teleportation. Although I have not witnessed this type of teleportation, other colleagues and friends have. One witness was a scientist friend of mine who was sitting next to an Orthodox monk-priest in an airplane that vanished from his seat before, after a long while, he suddenly reappeared. Not wanting to draw attention to himself, the monk suggested that my friend was mistaken. When my friend insisted that he was not, the monk told him that he was called to visit someone at a hospital who needed help. Although there are many well documented examples of Psychic Teleportation in history, I have much more compelling present-day anecdotal evidence that deserves investigating...

Jaunting was featured in Alfred Bester's "The Stars My Destination", concerning a misfit Gully Foyle, who learned instinctively how to "Jaunt" spontaneously, without the benefit of the public "Jaunting Pads" that had revolutionized travel across the Earth. 

This novella (along with Harlan Ellison's "A Boy And His Dog", check them BOTH out) were highly influential during my formative years. Thanks to the SciFi collection of the Doubleday Book Club in the early 70's....

So you've located some nifty earth-like exoplanets. And by all of the known laws of Physics, you're planning on getting humans there in a reasonable amount of time.. Exactly How???  These exoplanets are Many Light Years distant. And so far the only possibility of such a venture, is to combine the as yet unperfected Quantum Entanglement Teleportation, with the possibility of stabilized Quantum Level Micro Wormholes. (If they even exist at all.) Begging the question: Can CERN experimentation validate as to whether Quantum Level Micro Wormholes can actually exist? And.. If you could generate a Stable, Quantum Level Micro Wormhole, between two fixed points, What would you do with it?
MH 370 was teleported through the connecting tunnel with the reciprocal universe....hopefully they will emerge unscathed.

At first it was hard not to shop at Target.  It's getting easier and easier the more time goes on that you don't stop open carry.  And now you kicked out the Moms?
It's so hard for me to know which is the good guy and which is the bad guy.  Please advise.

Sorry, Beats Music can't bring me back to Target if you continue to welcome open-carry, while at the same time refusing to acknowledge the right of customers to feel safe and not shop next to extremists. Too bad, I've been a loyal customer for years.

Does your list include "Johnnie's Got a Gun or "hey Joe (whatcha doin with that gun in your hand?"  Not shopping here until you have no carry rules.

Dear target, 
It's been 2 months since I bought anything from you. I loved shopping in your stores and would spend 100's a month there. As a matter of fact you were my primary store to go to. It took a lot of will power to not have to "run to target" for this and that. Now I'm ordering on amazon and running to walgreens. Even my children stopped asking to go to target lately, guess they got into the habit of knowing that's no longer an option. I have no idea why you are taking this hard stance on allowing guns. I had always thought of target as classier than walmart but in reality I feel you are below walmart. You project a certain image and now you do this. Sadly to say I'm not only off target I'm over target. You have successfully ended my "addiction to shopping at target" the bright side I'm really racking up the reward points with amazon!! #overtarget

Since I don't wish to die while shopping, and since Open Carry begins in Kansas tomorrow, I will no longer be visiting Target. But make sure you keep up on my credit rating after giving away my personal information.
Calling Apple now at 1-800-275-2273 to let them know that Target is using their brand (Beats) to promote Open Carry while denying individuals the right to practice 1st Amendment protected protests.

Once again, I spent nearly $300 this weekend but NOT at #OffTarget. I will not shop at Target until they grow some #Gunsense. I shop for my family and for a nonprofit animal shelter and I spend about $300 every week. That's $15,600 annually. Bank on that cash going elsewhere, Target.

You've lost my business for good. That's 3 kids that need clothes and supplies versus the nutjob buying a bag of Oreos with a loaded AR-15. Does your PR team lick the markers that smell good? They seem to not grasp the big picture, and are a bit on the slow side.

you allow open carry members to parade their cause all around your store, but when peace loving women and children try to get their message out – in your parking lot- no less- you consider them a threat! So tell me how does it feel to intimidated by people with guns?

It's really kind of amazing to realize how far the Sun's corona extends... When I was a kid they taught us that the corona was the fringe of light that was visible around the eclipsed Sun, like what is visible in these pics. Later they said it extended further, 1 million miles. Now it's 5 million. The sun itself (what is covered by the black disk) is 864,000 miles across (1.4 million km), and when you add the visible portion of the corona, it's roughly a million miles across -- so what they've discovered means that the corona actually extends as far out as if you had five more suns extending out on all sides. Wow.

actor.description: Student at Indian Institute of Science

title.text: I want to build a intel mini fab model(kempf 2005) using arena please suggest some books.

comments.headline: Managing Director & Principal Consultant, Empirica Consulting Ltd

text.text: Rashmi, if you are new to using Arena, "Simulation with Arena" by David Kelton, et al., might be useful to get started.

comments.headline: Student at Indian Institute of Science

text.text: thanks a lot, please suggest some more books or reading materials as i am not getting an idea for preventive maintenance which need to be handled by technician.

comments.headline: Managing Director & Principal Consultant, Empirica Consulting Ltd

text.text: Rashmi, perhaps it would be useful to look through the papers or PhD thesis of Jose A. Ramirez-Hernandez. He handles the scheduling of technicians for preventative maintenance as an optimisation problem, solving it using an approximate dynamic programming algorithm. E.g., his 2010 paper might be a good place to start: "Optimization of Preventive Maintenance Scheduling in Semiconductor Manufacturing Models Using a Simulation-Based Approximate Dynamic Programming Approach".

Whenever I attend Emerald City Comicon, I spend an hour performing some material from my books and blog, and then take some questions at the end. In 2012, we realized that the awesome hour actually needed to be ninety minutes, because we had too much awesome to pack into the show. 

This is that show, including the Q&A at the end. I shared some silly stuff from my blog, including a dumb script I wrote imagining ROBOCOP as an 80s sit-com. I also read some unpublished material from an upcoming book called Memories of the Future Volume 2. Wil Wheaton's 90-Minute Awesome Hour at ECCC 2012

attachment.summary: Business is constantly changing and in today’s fast paced environment SMEs are faced with the task of sourcing new and innovative ways to improve their manufacturing design and operations. Simulation is one such avenue open to SMEs to improve...
attachment.title: Are SMEs Simulation-aware? - DCU Modelling and Simulation Research...

comments.headline: Simulation Professional at  Preferred Simulation Consultants, Inc.

text.text:
Having an effective simulation dept or group takes a commitment from the company needing to use this capability.  There is the investment in software and qualified full time resources.  Otherwise outside consultants are needed.  Either option may be considered too costly by unaware SME management.  Larger companies tend to have larger systems. The benefits of simulation can become more obvious and the costs more easily justified.  

I don't necessarily agree with that thinking but it seems to be a reality.  The answer really is that simulation consulting firms do need to fill this gap.   And they try.  Maybe it is a matter of time before more and more SMEs are convinced of the benefits or maybe it is more marketing of the simulation consultants.  Maybe a little of both.

comments.headline: Senior Research Fellow at Dublin City University - Business School

text.text:
Thanks for the comment Paul, yes I would be in agreement with you on the problems faced by SMEs in accessing simulation. We have made some arguments about this in a paper we presented in the 2013 Winter Simulation Conference, see here: http://informs-sim.org/wsc13papers/includes/files/013.pdf

Larger companies have larger budgets, more structured / more accessible data and potentially in-house expertise and experience of simulation, whereas SMEs struggle to deal with the complexity, expertise and costs involved.

We are trying to address this through developing Cloud based tools that are easier to use for SMEs supporting the simulation lifecycle, in this case focusing on the data collection phase.

You have raised an important issue. I am often surprised by how little simulation is known. I recently posted an article trying to describe the general ideas behind a simulation. The article can be accessed at:

https://www.linkedin.com/today/post/article/20140616184014-128460934-what-is-this-thing-called-simulation

actor.name: Nick B.
actor.description: Senior Consultant at West Monroe Partners

title.text: Looking for suggestions on any books and/or presentations that would be useful to provide management with to teach them the basics of modeling, simulation, and the development process.

comments.headline: Improving your profitability with Simio simulation and scheduling software.

text.text:
So you don't like my Arena book huh... :) Actually I agree that neither that text book nor my Simio text book are closely targeted enough at management to be the best choice. The Banks book discussed above is a great, well-written book, but it seems to me that might also be a bit too technical for most managers.

For a book targeted entirely at management I'd recommend you look at: Managing Change With Business Process Simulation: http://www.amazon.com/Managing-Change-Business-Process-Simulation/dp/0139058370

I might suggest that you also download chapter 1 of the Simio textbook. It is available free on-line (http://www.simio.com/publications/Simio-and-Simulation-Modeling-Analysis-Applications-Edition-03/preview/Simio_and_Simulation_PREVIEW_3e.pdf) and has a product independent management-level overview of simulation.

Another resource you might examine is the Success In Simulation blog (http://www.simio.com/blog/2008/04/28/success-in-simulation-introduction/). While not a book, this blog is product-independent and discusses many "Success" issues in small, easy to read, chunks. Many of these topics should be of interest to managers.

comments.headline: Senior Consultant at West Monroe Partners

text.text: Thank you David...I actually have your Arena book sitting on my desk and reference it multiple times a week.  Your book taught me simulation and how to code simulations in Arena.  As you pointed out in your suggestions I am looking for a book for management new to simulation to teach them about simulation without bogging them down with how to code a certain aspect.  I am finding more and more aside from this posting there are few books that teach simulation at a very high level.

Try this one: http://www.amazon.com/Fundamentals-Real-Time-Distributed-Simulation-Nicol/dp/0986841404/

It is also available on Lulu as an ebook here: http://www.lulu.com/shop/john-nicol/fundamentals-of-real-time-distributed-simulation/ebook/product-17409280.html

I wrote this specifically to provide an overview of distributed simulation as used in military or training environments when we need to connect simulators together. As opposed to academic and business modelling and simulation. It has chapters on models, terrain, DIS, HLA, VV&A, how to plan and execute M&S infrastructures and so on.

comments.headline: Managing Director & Principal Consultant, Empirica Consulting Ltd

text.text: Nick, already many good suggestions above. However, thinking about this from a slightly different angle, the following book is very good at explaining the frailties of human decision making and judgement when dealing with complex dynamic systems, and how simulation models can greatly assist in such areas; and I've found that senior managers often enjoy reading it. "The Logic of Failure: Recognizing and Avoiding Error in Complex Situations", Dietrich Dorner.

comments.headline: Senior Consultant at West Monroe Partners

text.text: Thank you to everyone for your suggestions.  I don't find it difficult to describe the methodology behind developing a computer simulation model, but I sometimes find it difficult to describe simulation without getting to far into the details. I think all of these suggestions are great and will serve their purpose to give my manager whom is new to simulation the depth of knowledge they need to understand simulation.

text.text:

376436_359090894161403_1614842519_n.jpg انسانیت را دوست می‌دارم، اما از خودم در شگفتم، هر چه بیشتر انسانیت را در مفهموم عام دوست می‌دارم، انسان را در مفهوم خاص، یعنی مجزا، به صورت فردی کمتر دوست می‌دارم.
در رویاهایم اغلب به طرح‌ریزی‌های ایثارگرانه برای خدمت به انسانیت رسیده‌ام و اگر ناگهان پای ضرورت به میان می‌آمد چه بسا با تصلیب رو به رو می‌شدم و با این همه، به تجربه می‌دانم که نمی‌توانم روی هم دو روز با کسی در یک اتاق سر کنم. همین که کسی نزدیکم باشد، رفتار او حرمتم را به هم می‌زند و آزادیم را محدود می‌کند....
امّا همیشه پیش آمده است که هر چه بیشتر از آدمها به طور فردی بیزار می‌شوم، عشقم به انسانیت شعله‌ورتر می‌شود.

فئودور داستایوسکی/برادران کارامازوف
content.header:
انسانیت را دوست می‌دارم، اما از خودم در شگفتم، هر چه بیشتر انسانیت را در مفهموم عام دوست می‌دارم، انسان را در مفهوم خاص، یعنی مجزا، به صورت فردی کمتر دوست می‌دارم.
در رویاهایم اغلب به طرح‌ریزی‌های ایثارگرانه برای خدمت به انسانیت رسیده‌ام و اگر ناگهان پای ضرورت به میان می‌آمد چه بسا با تصلیب رو به رو می‌شدم و با این همه، به تجربه می‌دانم که نمی‌توانم روی هم دو روز با کسی در یک اتاق سر کنم. همین که کسی نزدیکم باشد، رفتار او حرمتم را به هم می‌زند و آزادیم را محدود می‌کند....
امّا همیشه پیش آمده است که هر چه بیشتر از آدمها به طور فردی بیزار می‌شوم، عشقم به انسانیت شعله‌ورتر می‌شود.

title.text: Training Simulations with Generic or Specific Equipment?

summary.text:
Can anyone direct me to a study comparing the impacts of providing simulation training that uses generic equipment as compared to specific brand names? 
As the providers of simulations for workplace training, there is always the concern that these debates will dominate our next holiday party.

text.text: Yes, there is one that I'm looking at and possibly approaching with a view to helping them grow their business as well as possibly providing a career path for me. I've been working with them on a motion control upgrade project for a private client of mine this last few months and when I see the other very promising projects they have just won contracts for starting in May, I can see that they have much promise. I'm not at liberty to mention details of the company or projects at this time.

Hi Jay, if you're into Flight Simulation, as I am, you can find a starter document at ARINC which may help with evaluating quality and all sorts of metrics by which to perform such. It's not free, but a good starter is ARINC 433-2
I will follow up for sure, thanks for your guidance, Suzanne.
